\f0\fs24 \cf0 Document: Full-Scope Expansion Plan for after-effects-mcp\
Objective\
Evolve after-effects-mcp from a useful AE automation bridge into a more complete, reliable, and LLM-friendly wrapper around the After Effects ExtendScript DOM, while preserving backward compatibility and minimizing disruption to existing users.\
Repository Context\
- Repo: /Users/bhupendrasharma/Documents/after-effects-mcp\
- Runtime: Node.js + TypeScript, ESM\
- Main entry: src/index.ts\
- AE bridge: src/scripts/mcp-bridge-auto.jsx\
- Current design:\
  - monolithic server registration in src/index.ts\
  - file-based command/result bridge\
  - many layer/effect/text/render tools already implemented\
- Constraints:\
  - preserve existing public behavior where practical\
  - do not hand-edit build/\
  - ExtendScript compatibility matters\
  - AI/LLM usage is a first-class design goal\
Primary Goals\
- Add missing high-value AE DOM coverage.\
- Standardize tool contracts, errors, identifiers, and serialization.\
- Improve bridge robustness and observability.\
- Make the system safer and more predictable for LLM-driven workflows.\
- Refactor architecture incrementally around stable abstractions.\
- Improve documentation and testing enough to support confident autonomous coding.\
Non-Goals\
- Do not aim for 100% theoretical AE DOM exposure in the first pass.\
- Do not redesign transport unless current file-based transport proves insufficient.\
- Do not break existing public tools unless absolutely necessary.\
- Do not overbuild meta-infrastructure before core contracts are stable.\
High-Level Strategy\
Implement in this order:\
1. Define contracts first.\
2. Improve bridge diagnostics and normalization.\
3. Build shared ExtendScript helpers.\
4. Add read-only introspection tools first.\
5. Add safe mutation primitives.\
6. Expand breadth of coverage by domain.\
7. Refactor server structure around proven abstractions.\
8. Harden docs/tests and migrate legacy behavior gradually.\
--------------------------------------------------\
PHASE 0 - Scope, Compatibility, and Guardrails\
--------------------------------------------------\
Purpose\
Establish boundaries so implementation does not sprawl or accidentally break compatibility.\
Deliverables\
- Supported AE version policy.\
- Compatibility policy for current tool names.\
- Capability boundary statement.\
- Rollout/migration policy.\
Implementation Requirements\
- Keep current kebab-case tools as canonical public names.\
- Keep current camelCase aliases for backward compatibility.\
- Document supported host assumptions:\
  - AE versions supported\
  - OS assumptions\
  - ExtendScript limitations\
- Define \'93practical coverage\'94 target:\
  - project\
  - composition\
  - layer\
  - property\
  - effects\
  - text\
  - shapes\
  - render\
  - project items\
  - source replacement\
- Explicitly mark some capabilities as version-dependent or unsupported.\
Acceptance Criteria\
- There is a written compatibility policy.\
- There is a written support matrix skeleton.\
- New work is scoped against explicit target domains.\
--------------------------------------------------\
PHASE 1 - Core Contract Design\
--------------------------------------------------\
Purpose\
Lock down the most important shared abstractions before adding many new tools.\
1.1 Response Envelope\
Design\
All new tools, and migrated existing tools, should converge on a standard envelope:\
interface AEResponse<T = unknown> \{\
  status: "success" | "error";\
  command: string;\
  commandId?: string;\
  timestamp: string;\
  data?: T;\
  error?: \{\
    code: string;\
    message: string;\
    rawMessage?: string;\
    retryable?: boolean;\
    userActionable?: boolean;\
    details?: unknown;\
  \};\
  warnings?: Array<\{\
    code?: string;\
    message: string;\
    details?: unknown;\
  \}>;\
  meta?: \{\
    versionDependent?: boolean;\
    hostVersion?: string;\
    truncated?: boolean;\
    nextHandles?: unknown;\
  \};\
  raw?: unknown;\
\}\
Rules\
- status is always present.\
- command is always present.\
- data exists only on success.\
- error exists only on failure.\
- raw may contain raw AE/bridge details for debugging.\
- meta.nextHandles should expose useful follow-up identifiers where possible.\
1.2 Error Taxonomy\
Design\
Introduce normalized error codes:\
- APP_NOT_AVAILABLE\
- PROJECT_NOT_OPEN\
- COMP_NOT_FOUND\
- LAYER_NOT_FOUND\
- ITEM_NOT_FOUND\
- PROP_NOT_FOUND\
- EFFECT_NOT_FOUND\
- INVALID_IDENTIFIER\
- INVALID_VALUE\
- UNSUPPORTED_OPERATION\
- VERSION_UNSUPPORTED\
- TIMEOUT\
- BRIDGE_STALE_RESULT\
- BRIDGE_MALFORMED_RESULT\
- INTERNAL_ERROR\
Rules\
- Map raw ExtendScript exceptions into one of these where possible.\
- Preserve original raw exception text in rawMessage.\
- Mark retryable vs fatal.\
1.3 Identifier Strategy\
Design\
Support multiple lookup strategies, but prefer stability:\
- IDs when AE exposes them\
- names for user convenience\
- indexes as fallback for ordered structures\
- canonical property paths for nested properties\
Rules\
- Reads may accept name/index/ID.\
- Writes should return IDs and canonical handles in their response.\
- Responses should include both stable and human-readable identifiers.\
Recommended Types\
interface CompHandle \{\
  compId?: number;\
  compName?: string;\
  compIndex?: number;\
\}\
interface LayerHandle \{\
  layerId?: number;\
  layerName?: string;\
  layerIndex?: number;\
\}\
interface ItemHandle \{\
  itemId?: number;\
  itemName?: string;\
  itemIndex?: number;\
\}\
1.4 Property Path Specification\
This is critical and must be designed early.\
Requirements\
- Must support nested properties.\
- Must support indexed groups.\
- Should support matching by display name and matchName.\
- Must round-trip from introspection to read/write tools.\
Recommended Path Model\
Use structured property paths internally, optionally allow string shorthand externally.\
interface PropertyPathSegment \{\
  name?: string;\
  matchName?: string;\
  index?: number;\
\}\
interface PropertyPath \{\
  segments: PropertyPathSegment[];\
\}\
Optional External Shorthand\
Allow string paths for convenience, but normalize immediately.\
Examples:\
- Transform.Position\
- ADBE Transform Group > ADBE Position\
- structured segments\
Rules\
- Introspection tools must return canonical structured property paths.\
- Mutation tools should accept both canonical structured paths and compatible shorthand if easy to normalize.\
- Avoid relying on display names only.\
1.5 Value Serialization Spec\
This is the second critical foundation.\
Requirements\
Support:\
- scalar numbers\
- booleans\
- strings\
- 2D/3D arrays\
- color values\
- shape/path values\
- text document snapshots\
- enums\
- keyframe values with metadata\
Recommended Shapes\
type SerializedValue =\
  | \{ type: "number"; value: number; units?: string \}\
  | \{ type: "boolean"; value: boolean \}\
  | \{ type: "string"; value: string \}\
  | \{ type: "vector2"; value: [number, number]; units?: string \}\
  | \{ type: "vector3"; value: [number, number, number]; units?: string \}\
  | \{ type: "color"; value: [number, number, number] | [number, number, number, number] \}\
  | \{ type: "enum"; value: string | number; label?: string \}\
  | \{ type: "textDocument"; value: Record<string, unknown> \}\
  | \{ type: "shapePath"; value: Record<string, unknown> \}\
  | \{ type: "unknown"; value: unknown \};\
Rules\
- Use explicit type tags.\
- Preserve enough information for round-trip mutation where feasible.\
- Include units when derivable.\
Acceptance Criteria for Phase 1\
- Written contract definitions exist for envelope, errors, identifiers, property paths, and serialized values.\
- At least one server-side normalization layer exists for results/errors.\
- All future feature work references these contracts.\
--------------------------------------------------\
PHASE 2 - Bridge Diagnostics and Runtime Robustness\
--------------------------------------------------\
Purpose\
Improve reliability and debuggability before expanding feature count.\
Current Context\
- src/index.ts handles queue/write/wait/clear logic inline.\
- File-based bridge is simple but vulnerable to stale results and opaque failures.\
Deliverables\
- dedicated bridge module\
- health/status tool\
- capability/version handshake\
- structured diagnostics\
- improved stale-result and malformed-result handling\
Implementation Tasks\
- Extract bridge helpers from src/index.ts into a bridge-focused module.\
- Create a bridge health tool returning:\
  - bridge available?\
  - last result timestamp\
  - bridge version\
  - supported command registry version if possible\
- Add richer diagnostic statuses:\
  - command written\
  - result pending\
  - stale result\
  - malformed result\
  - timeout\
  - host unavailable\
- Preserve current file transport for now.\
- Add debug mode to optionally capture raw payloads for reproduction.\
Important Constraint\
Do not redesign transport to queues/per-command files unless actual concurrency bugs are observed in real usage.\
Acceptance Criteria\
- Bridge logic is isolated.\
- There is a machine-readable health check.\
- Timeout/stale/malformed failures are distinguishable.\
--------------------------------------------------\
PHASE 3 - Shared ExtendScript Runtime Foundation\
--------------------------------------------------\
Purpose\
Reduce duplication and inconsistency in the large bridge script.\
Current Context\
- src/scripts/mcp-bridge-auto.jsx is large and mixes many command handlers.\
- Many commands likely resolve comps/layers/items independently.\
Deliverables\
- shared resolver helpers\
- shared serialization helpers\
- consistent command wrapper behavior\
- version/capability checks\
Required Shared JSX Helpers\
- resolveComp(args)\
- resolveLayer(comp, args)\
- resolveProjectItem(args)\
- resolvePropertyPath(target, propertyPath)\
- serializeValue(value, propertyMeta?)\
- serializeLayer(layer)\
- serializeComp(comp)\
- serializeItem(item)\
- serializeError(error, context)\
- withUndoGroup(label, fn)\
- supportsFeature(featureName)\
Rules\
- Every command uses shared try/catch behavior.\
- Every command returns the normalized response envelope.\
- Shared serializers should be reused across all read/write commands.\
- All mutations should be wrapped in undo groups where feasible.\
Acceptance Criteria\
- Repeated resolver logic is centralized.\
- New commands can be added with minimal boilerplate.\
- Output shapes are visibly more consistent.\
--------------------------------------------------\
PHASE 4 - Read-Only Introspection First\
--------------------------------------------------\
Purpose\
Give the LLM eyes before giving it more hands.\
This is the highest-value phase for reliable AI-driven control.\
4.1 Property Introspection Tools\
New Tools\
- inspect-property-tree\
- list-properties\
- get-property-metadata\
- get-property-value\
- get-expression\
Expected Behavior\
- inspect-property-tree\
  - returns nested property hierarchy\
  - includes canonical property paths for all children\
  - includes useful metadata: name, matchName, type, depth, canSetExpression, isTimeVarying, numKeys\
- list-properties\
  - lightweight flattened list of property paths and names\
- get-property-metadata\
  - type, dimensions, units if derivable, expression support, keyframe count, read-only/writeable hints\
- get-property-value\
  - read current or time-sampled property value in normalized serialized format\
- get-expression\
  - returns current expression and enabled state if supported\
4.2 Project/Item Read Tools\
New Tools\
- list-project-items\
- get-project-item-info\
- get-project-structure or folder-tree equivalent\
Expected Behavior\
- Include item IDs, types, names, folder relationships, source info where available.\
4.3 Composition Read Tools\
New Tools\
- get-composition-settings\
- optional work area/advanced settings readers\
Expected Behavior\
- duration\
- frame rate\
- dimensions\
- background color\
- work area\
- motion blur related settings where available\
- shutter settings where available\
Rules for All Introspection Tools\
- Return stable handles and follow-up-ready paths/IDs.\
- Prefer concise default output and explicit expansion modes if output is large.\
- Include truncation metadata when necessary.\
- Provide child handles in meta.nextHandles.\
Acceptance Criteria\
- An LLM can inspect a comp/layer/property tree and derive exact identifiers for follow-up mutation.\
- Property values are available in a consistent typed format.\
